The provided sources outline the fundamentals of effective communication in English, focusing on the four integrated language skills: Listening, Speaking, Reading, and Writing (LSRW). Effective communication is defined by its communicability—the ability to translate ideas into simple, easily understood sentences so the receiver gets the message without distortion.
Integrated Language Skills (LSRW)
•	Receptive Skills (Listening and Reading): These are often mistakenly called "passive," but they are highly active mental processes involving decoding and interpreting input.
•	Productive Skills (Speaking and Writing): These involve generating output. Speaking requires intelligibility and fluency (continuity of ideas), while writing is a "crafted skill" that requires structured instruction.
Frameworks for Effective Writing
Writing is the most complex cognitive language skill. The sources highlight two primary frameworks to master it:
1.	CODER Principle: Collect, Organize, Draft, Edit, and Review.
2.	POWER Strategy: Prepare, Organize, Write, Evaluate, and Review.
Good writing must be brief, clear, objective, and specific. Writers are encouraged to avoid "ornamental" language, sexist expressions, and vague or derogatory remarks. Instead, they should customize their style based on the needs and technical level of their audience.
