Example: Writing a Letter of Requisition
Using the POWER strategy, the sources illustrate how to write a formal request to a librarian for a refund of a library caution deposit.
•	1. Prepare (Brainstorming): Note down all necessary points without self-censorship, such as your status as a graduating student, the specific refund amount (e.g., Rs. 2000), and the reason for the request.
•	2. Organize: Act as a "tour guide" for the reader. Decide that the letter should start with an introduction/reason for writing, followed by supporting details of the payment, and conclude with the specific request for action.
•	3. Write: Expand the organized points into full sentences. At this stage, focus on the flow of ideas rather than perfect grammar or spelling.
•	4. Evaluate: Proofread for errors. For example, the writer might correct a misspelling of "semester," capitalize the "Student Book Loan Scheme," or change a casual phrase like "write back to me" to a more professional request for a refund.
•	5. Review: Perform a final check to ensure the tone is appropriately formal and polite. It is helpful to read the work aloud to see if it sounds natural or to have a friend provide feedback
